<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Wall oven door issues</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Hinge sag, glass damage, gasket compression, door switch. Built-in adds two complications.</h2>

    <p>Wall oven door issues split into four categories: hinge sag (year 7 to 10 typical, double-oven lower cavity fails 3 to 4 years before upper), gasket compression (year 8 to 10), inner pane glass damage, and door switch fault. The mechanics are the same as free-standing range doors. The differences on built-in wall ovens are two specific complications.</p>

    <p>First, hinge access on most wall oven brands requires partial unit pull from the cabinet. The hinges mount through the unit's front frame and into the door, and on premium brands the access path runs through the cabinet trim. Labor uplift over a free-standing range hinge replacement runs $200 to $400 depending on brand and configuration.</p>

    <p>Second, premium German tier (Wolf E-series, Miele PureLine, Thermador Professional, Gaggenau BO and BS) uses Schott Ceran ceramic glass for the inner pane. Brand-specific, generation-specific, sourced through the manufacturer's authorized parts pipeline in Europe with 4 to 6 week import lead times. Generic ceramic glass with a different thermal expansion coefficient cracks again within months because the heat-cycle stress profile does not match the door frame. We use authorized OEM only on these.</p>

    <p><strong>$89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair.</strong> BHGS Licensed #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). 90-day warranty. Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. For free-standing range door diagnostic, see <a href="/services/oven-repair/door-issues/">oven door issues</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TOP 5 ISSUES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Top 5 wall oven door issues</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">In honest frequency order.</h2>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>1. Hinge sag (year 7 to 10, double-oven lower fails first)</h3>
      <p>Heavy-duty spring hinges hold the weight of glass and door panel. Over years the spring tension fades and the door starts to drop. Symptom: top corner gap when door is closed, or door swings open if not fully latched. On double ovens the lower cavity hinges sag 3 to 4 years before the upper because of cabinet heat trap, more daily use, and higher cycle count. Mid-tier paired set $200 to $380; pro-tier (Wolf, Miele, Thermador) $600 to $900 paired.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>2. Door gasket compression (year 8 to 10)</h3>
      <p>Silicone or rubber gasket loses memory over years of door cycling. Gap between door and frame develops, oven loses heat during cooking, dishes cook unevenly. Mid-tier gasket $80 to $180 part (DIY-friendly on most). Pro-tier German tier $260 to $480 with door panel removal and authorized parts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>3. Inner pane glass crack (Schott Ceran on premium German tier)</h3>
      <p>Wolf E-series, Miele PureLine, Thermador Professional, Gaggenau BO and BS use Schott Ceran ceramic glass for the inner door pane. When it cracks (thermal stress, impact, or self-clean cycle), replacement requires authorized German-manufactured glass with the correct thermal expansion coefficient. 4 to 6 week parts lead. Generic substitutes fail again within months. Pro-tier replacement $700 to $1,400. Mid-tier inner pane $300 to $560 standard tempered glass, faster sourcing.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>4. Door switch fault</h3>
      <p>Light always on or never on; oven refuses to start because safety interlock reads door always open. Switch is a small mechanical part, $200 to $340 mid-tier replacement, $340 to $540 pro-tier.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>5. Self-clean door lock failure</h3>
      <p>Self-clean cycle locks the door for safety during 900°F+ operation. After cycle, the lock motor or its electronic latch sometimes fails to release. We cover this on <a href="/services/wall-oven-repair/control-board-failure/">control board failure</a> because the lock motor often shares board with the main control. The fix overlaps but the diagnostic context starts with the cycle, not general door wear.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 DOUBLE OVEN EXPANSION -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Double oven door pattern (lower fails first)</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Asymmetric wear is the diagnostic key on doubles.</h2>

    <p>On double wall ovens (GE Profile JT, KitchenAid Architect KODE, Whirlpool WOD, Wolf E-series DO30, Miele H 7440, Thermador Professional ME302), lower cavity components age faster than upper across the board. Hinges are the most visible example.</p>

    <p>Why the lower fails first:</p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Cabinet heat trap.</strong> Heat rises during cooking. Lower cavity sits in elevated ambient between cycles, components accumulate thermal stress at higher rates.</li>
      <li><strong>Daily use frequency.</strong> Lower cavity used 60 to 70% of cooking sessions in typical household. Upper used for larger occasions or when both cooked simultaneously.</li>
      <li><strong>Door weight cycling.</strong> Lower door opened and closed more times, hinges cycle more, springs fatigue earlier.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The diagnostic application: when lower hinges sag at year 9, the upper hinges are typically 60 to 80% along the same wear curve. Proactive replacement of both pairs in a single visit costs $120 to $200 extra in parts but saves a full second service call within 12 to 24 months. We recommend it on doubles past year 8.</p>

    <p>Same pattern on bake elements, sensors, and door switches: lower fails first, upper follows. See <a href="/services/wall-oven-repair/double-oven-issues/">double oven issues</a> for the full configuration walkthrough.</p>
  </div>
</section>

